{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/0051415689A/1958030701/0341.xml":{"full_text":"_\n_.President\n_Vice-President\n.secretary- Treasurer\nMILFORD CHRONICLE\nESTABLISHED OCTOBER 4, 187\u00bb _\nTHEO. TOWNSEND\nEditor and Proprietor from 1878 to 1910\nMILFORD CHRONICLE PUBLISHING COMPANY\n10 TO 1\u00ab SOUTH WEST FRONT STREET\nMILFORD, DELAWARE\nPUBLISHERS\n\nO. Marshall Townsend.\nVirginia S. Townsend.\nTheodore Townsend_\n_Editor\n.Managing Editor\nO. Marshall Townsend...\nRobert H. Yerkee_\nExclusive National Advertising Representative\nGreater Weeklies\nNew York Chicago Detroit Philadelphia\nSubscription Terms\nBy Mall\u2014In Delaware. S3.60 a Tear\nOuuide of Delaware, $3.00 a Year\n-Six Cental\nBlngle Copies_\nPHONE\u2014MILFORD 4521\nAddress all communications to the Milford Chronicle\nPublishing Company, Milford, Delaware*\nEntered as second-class matter March 3, 1119 at the\npost attic* at Milford, Del., under Act of March 3, 1179\nDBLAware's LEADING weekly newspaper\nnew\u00ef\u00ef,V\u00ee^!Stb S l \u00efS5ofpip\u00abS e i\u00ef\u00ef\u00efb\u00eep o\u00bb 1 p\u00abS prtrt\u00ef\u00ef\n\u00c4i' 0 cb n 'J. u r X5 a kd'v n e ,1 r,l\u00c4 \u25a0'\u2022\u00c4TatTS\nguaranteed circulation of over 7,000 copies each issue.\nMEMber ofthe associated PRESS\nTh\u00ab Associnted Press is entitled exclusively to the\nUds newspap^l\u00b0as\u00b0wen f as' ap\u00b0 ne ws e di *patches!* ln\nFRIDAY, MARCH 7, 1958\nON WITH THE RECESSION\nThe announcement has been made in\nWashington that unemployment in the Uni\nted States has now reached 5,000,000 per\nsons. That is a pretty fair percentage of the\ntotal number of working Americans.\nThis is of great concern to every govern\nment economist and every U. S. citizen be\ncause when unemployment reaches this to\ntal, with prices and wages continuing to go\nup\u2014as sales go down in a number of phases\nof the economy\u2014something is obviously out\nof kilter.\nIn fact, the is now at a crucial\npoint along the road to tomorrow. Either\nwe have an upturn soon or we move into a\ndepression. Car inventories are piling up,\nsteel is slow (estimated at fifty-five per cent\nof productive capacity) and plant expansion\nis being reduced considerably.\nThis, combined with a farm recession,\nnow in its fourth or fifth year, and farm\npolicies which are failing, necessitate large\ngovernmental outlays to prevent the depres\nsion that could occur without heavy federal\nspending, including defense spending.\nWe do not think a depression will follow,\nlargely because of high levels of defense and\nother government spending. But this will\nbe an artificial prop to the economy, that will\nprobably cause some more inflation, and\nwhich will probably leave the economy\u2014\neventually\u2014in a more precarious position\nthan it was in before, or is in right now.\nWhat is needed is permanently sound\nfarm legislation,* labor legislation, and in\nflation controls, so that the eventual read\njustment will not be severe. The present ad\njustment would be far more severe were it\nnot for the international situation, armed\nservices payrolls, unemployment payments,\nsocial security income and local and state\ngovernment expenditures, which are at a\nhigh level.\nPresident Eisenhower says the economy\nwill experience an upturn by the summer,\nand hints that he will favor a cut in taxes if\nthere is no such upturn. However, if there\nisn't, Congress will then be adjourning, and\nany tax action would have to wait until 1959.\nIn the meantime, if the Administration is\nmisjudging the situation, the recession could\ngrow more severe.\nPRODUCTIVE CAPACITY\nOne of the major questions posed by the\ncurrent recession has nothing to do with op\ntimism or pessimism, faith in America or\nlack of faith in America, the election of Dem\nocrats or of Republicans. This question is\nfactual: Have increases in productive capac\nity outstripped employment?\nIn other words, can the American econ\nomy now produce so much more with fewer\nworkers than it could 10 years ago that few\ner workers are needed in manufacturing in\ndustries? Too many people today talk about\nthe recession and the American economy\nwithout thinking much about automation,\nwhich has been quite rapidly introduced in\nAmerica during the last few years. Along\nwith automation, we are witnessing the de\nvelopment of new skilled workers, especially\nas a result of recent technological advances\nand the development of thermonuclear en\nergy. Older skilled and semi-skilled workers\nare threatened.\nAutomation can be a boon if displaced\nworkers are re-trained for other jobs, and if\nthe effects of automation are cushioned.\nOtherwise, it can wreak havoc on American\nworking people. These are all factors in\nvolved in the recession. They should be\nthought about seriously, but outside the usu\nal framework of politics and.optimism ver\nsus pessimism.\nA HOPE FOR TAX RELIEF\nThe steeply graduated rates of our pres\nent income tax structure confiscate up to 91\nper cent of individual earnings and levy a\n52 per cent tax on corporate income.\nCongressman Sadlak, a Republican, and\nCongressman Ilerlong, a Democrat, have in\ntroduced a bill which would remove the road\nblocks to the industrial expansion and re\nsearch needed to create more jobs and raise\nliving standards. Their bill would give tax\nrelief to both individual and corporate Fed\neral taxpayers, with a 42 per cent top for\nboth individuals and corporations. The cuts\nwould be made gradually over a five-year per\niod and because normal economic growth\nwould expand Federal revenue, the Trea\nsury would not suffer.\nThe Sadlak-Herlong bill would go a long\nway toward removing the shadow of confis\ncatory taxation that looms large over every\nbusiness conference table, disrupting indus\ntry's traditional function of planning and\nproviding for the expansion, research, plant\nmaintenance and job opportunities that have\nmade America the most prosperous nation\non earth.\nPROPER TAX CUT BILL\nDEPENDS ON HOME SUPPORT\nSentiment in the House Ways and Means\nCommittee is increasing some form of tax\nreduction in the next few months. Members\nof that committee were deeply impressed by\nthe need for tax rate reform during the twen\nty-four days of hearings recently completed.\n\nA large number of representatives of em\nployer groups appeared before the Commit\ntee to plead the cause of sound tax rate re\nform. They made an excellent impression.\nThat impression must not be allowed to die\nfrom lack of further support.\nIf business is to be freed of some of the\nstraight-jacket restrictions imposed under\nthe present tax structure, now is the time to\ninsist upon proper tax legislation. Don't wait\nuntil House members have committed them\nselves to the wrong kind of tax reduction\nbill.\nThe need for immediate action is increas\ned by learning of labor leaders' plans. Hun\ndreds of union officials are expected to des\ncend on Washington the second week in\nMarch. They intend to buttonhole Congress\nmen and push their plans for HlCOme tax re\nduction almost entirely in the low bracket\nrates as well as increased unemployment ben\nefits, Social Security programs, and other\nfederal spending programs.\nMost favored by business are the Sadlak\nHerlong bills (H. R, 6452 and H. R, 9119) to\nreduce individual and corporate rates. This\nlegislation provides for tax reduction over\nfive years (to be spread to nine years, if nec\nessary) of all corporate and individual tax\nrat\nno need for figuring angles or requiring spe\ncial legislation. Both individuals and busi\nnesses would eventually have a 427\u00bb maxi\nmum rate,\nThis new approach to tax reduction has\na number of points in its favor. Among them\nare:\nIt avoids the \"gimmick\" or piecemeal ap\nproach to the tax problem. There would be\nIt would more than pay for itself. Tax re\nductions under the bill would amount to ap\nproximately $3 billion a year. Tax revenue\nin recent years had been growing at about\n$4 billion a year, until interrupted by the\npresent recession. Lessening the restraints\nnow crippling business expansion would pro\nvide for increased growth, in turn providing\ngreater tax revenues for balancing the bud\nget and essential federal expenditures,\nIt applies to all groups. Rate reduction is\nincluded for every bracket of taxpayer, indi\nvidual or business,\nIt allows accumulation of investment cap\nital and encourages growth. The present tax\nstructure is a deterrent to corporate growth\no yer the $25,000 earning level, where the tax\njumps from 30% to 52%. Also by reducing\nthe steep progressive individual rates,\nunincorporated business, the bulk of all bus\ninesses, is given the most meaningful kind of\ntax help.\nIt is a long term plan. Taxpayers could\nplan ahead with reasonable certainty of their\ntax obligations. And if found necessary, the\nmeasure provides for one year postponements\nwhich could stretch the reductions from five\nto nine years.\nThe Sadlak-Herlong bill is a sound tax\nmeasure and it should be given thoughtful\nconsideration by every member of Congress,\nWrite your Congressman today and suggest\nthat he take a good, long, serious look at this\nbill before making a final decision on the type\nof tax reduction the country needs. This is\na critical time in the development of a tax\nreduction measure. Members of Congress\nneed and want your views\u2014they are entitled\nto them. And your letters can be very influ\nential in guiding Congress toward the type\nof sound, constructive tax reduction which\nthe country so desperately needs.\nnot already been covered more eloquently\nbefore\u2014by someone else. Nevertheless, those\ncharged with the responsibility of writing\neditorials for the nation's press cannot see\nAN AMERICAN PLAGUE\nOne of the unbelievable things about our\ngreat country is that we continue to allow\nthe slaughter of a hundred citizens a day on\nour highways and city streets. There is\nnothing that can be written about this cancer\nin our American way of life that will change\nthe situation overnight.\nThere is little to be written which has\nthe continuing carnage of the highways, year\nafter year, with a stilled and quiet pen.\nWhat is to be done about the killing,\nwhich is more deadly than any war? If we\nare so emotionally disturbed (and right\nfully) about the slaughter of mankind in\nwars, why are we less disturbed by equally\nunjust killings of little children, boys and\ngirls and adults, by automobiles and trucks,\nBy drunken, careless, or unlicensed drivers?\nNo one answer can be offered as a solu\ntion to the great American oddity. The only\nsolution lies in a thoroughly aroused public\nopinion, which in its wrath, will finally de\nmand that adequate steps be taken to curb\nthe slaughter. When this day comes, pa\ntience with drunken driving, with unsafe\nvehicles, with repeated offenses, and with\nflagrant violations of speed and safety laws\nwill end.\nTheh, the American people will grow up\nand take driving seriously, and reduce the\nnumber of tragic deaths of children and\nadults alike\u2014many of whom die through\nno fault of their own, only to have society do\ncomparatively nothing to punish their killer\nsimple facts give you a clue to what has\nbeen happening in American industry:\n''Fact one is that output of goods in fac\ntories for each man-hour of work has risen\nby high and rising prices. This is the kind\nof inflation that has destroyed currencies and\nbrought collapse to governments all through\nhistory.\nAN OLD STORY\nU. S. News and World Report says; \"Two\nonly a trifle more than 1 per cent in the two\nyears since 1955.\n\"Fact two is that hourly pay of factory\nworkers has in that tame period gone up\na bit more than 10 per cent.\nThis trend could produce something new\nin this country\u2014a depression accompanied\nALL IN ONE BIG BASKET\nKsr\nV\n\n\n\u2022T\n\nm\n~y.\n\n'O e*\n(jOP\nm\nx--;\nU%\nU\n\nt\nI\ny\nJM\n\n\n\u2022SK;\n\n\nIII\n\u25a0a\nelect io*U\n\n\n\n\nl\u00fc\nV V\n\nx' J6&\na\n\nY y\nf\nB\nV/\n\nv\nSS?\n2-385\n-v\n0\n:2\nx\n>4]\n*2Scr.\niS \u00c9\u00dc\u00dc\nBA5S0N DISCUSSES IMPORTANCE OF TIME\nBabscs Parli, Mass., March 6. 1\nSome wise man said that when any\none steals om money, we have a\nchance to get it back; but when\nanyone steals our time, we can\nnever replace it. This is true\nwhether it refers simply to being\nlate to appointments, or whether it\nconcerns strikes, idleness, or\nworking efficiently. i\nHow Large Fortunes Are Made\nHowever, this week I will write of\nan entirely different use of TIME,\u2014\nnamely, in connection with iucreas\ning the value of our investments,\nin fact, time and patience have\nbeen the making of most large\nfortunes. Of course, one must use\nintelligence and diversification, but\nthe truly important requirement\nis TIME.\nMost readers know that if they\nshould promise to pay some person\none cent the first day and two\ncents the second day and four cents\nthe third day, and eight cents\nthe fourth day, and so on, doub\nling each day for a month, the\nresult will be fantastic. For the 31st\nday of the month, they would have\nto pay the person about $10,000,000!\nThis is the way most large family\nfortunes have been created, by\nTIME.\nHow To Become A Millionaire\nIf you substitute years for days,\nstart with one dollar instead of a\npenny and double the amount of\nyour investment only once each\nLINCOLN\nMrs. Rena Morgan\nPhone: Milford 6189\nLincoln Methodist Church'\nRev. W. W. Hamilton, Pastor\nServices for Sunday, March 9:\n10 a. m. Morning Worship Hour.\nThe Choir will be using for their\nspecial \"Others.\"\n11 a. m. Church School Session.\nDouglas Morgan, superintendent;\nPaul White, assistant superinten\ndent. Newcomers and visitors are\nalways welcome. Make this a fam\nily church, not only for Sunday\nSchool but for worship service as\nwell.\n4 to 4:30 p. m. \"Precious Mem\nories Broadcast\" over Georgetown\nStation, 900 on the dial.\n6:30 p. m. MYF under the di\nrection of Albert Coleman, coun\nselor. All youth in and around this\ncommunity are cordially invited to\nattend.\n7:30 p. m. Evening song and\npraise service. You will be bless\ned as you join friends in the wor\nship of the Lord.\n.Thursday evening, choir prac\ntice, 7 to 7:30 o'clock.\nThe Friendship Bible Class will\nmeet this Tuesday evening, March\n11, at the home of Mrs. Mae Mor\ngan. Text word \"Youth.\" A cor\ndial invitation is extended to all.\nA ham and oyster supper, fam\nily style, will be held Saturday eve\nning, March 15, at the New Lincoln\nCommunity Center, sponsored by\nthe Boy Scout Troop No. 307 of\nLincoln. Price. $1.25\u201475c. Tickets\nare now available from any mem\nber of the troop or Harry Glasco.\nThere will be a regular meeting\nof the Ladies' Auxiliary on Mon\nday evening, March 10, at the Lin\ncoln Community Center. All mem\nbers please try to attend to dis\ncuss plans for the Easter flower\nsale.\nThe wedding of Miss Joyce E.\nBennett, daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nWilliam H. Bennett, of Lincoln,\n\u00abid John R. Clark, son of Mrs.\nLulu Clark of Truitt avenue, Mil\nford, took place Saturday, March 1.\nat the First Baptist Church in Mil\nford. The Rev. Thomas G. Harris,\npastor of the First Baptist Church,\nperformed the ceremony. Their at\ntendants were Mr. and Mrs. Albert\nStokes.\nMiss Bennett is a graduate of\nMilton High School, class of 1957.\nMr. Clark is a graduate of Milford\nHigh School, class of 1951. Mr.\nClark served in the U. S. Army and\nis now a journeyman in the meat\ndepartment of the Dover A. and P.\nThey are at home at 217 South\nWashington street, Milford.\nStore.\nThe wedding of Miss Elaine Bee\nr. and Mrs. Har\nerald Smith, son\n\nbe. daughter of\nry Beebe, and\nof Mr. and Mrs. James Smith, also\nof Lincoln, took place Saturday af\nternoon at 2 p. m. in Denton. Md.,\nyear, you could have over $100,000,\n000 at the end of 31 years, after\ntaxes, losses, trust and other fees,\nCertainly, with proper advice you\ncan select each year\u2014except in bear\nmarkets\u2014some stock selling at one\nor two dollars a share which is al\nmost certain to double within one\nPlease note carefully that I\ndo not say you can expect this\nsame stock to double every follow\ning year,\nThis means that when this cheap\nstock doubles in value, your broker\nneed only sell this stock and re\ninvest the money in some other\ncheap stock which will probably\ndouble in one year. I am not count\ning dividends in the above calcu\nlations the stocks which are se\nlected will be cheap \u00fbon-dividend\npaying stocks. But this also means\nyou will haye no income taxes to\npay,\u2014only the Federal and State\n\"profits\" or \"intangible\" taxes, ac\ncording to where you live,\nThe Fly In The Ointment?\nYou say that there must be some\ntrick in this story of mine. There\nmay be: it probably is that making\nthese millions from one dollar in\n31 years without borrowing a penny j\nmay depend upon not too many\nbrokers recommending the same\nstock. Also, there could be difficulty\nin either obtaining or selling such\nlarge number of shares.\nHowever, remember that the\nabove illustration is based upon\nwith Rev. Thomas J. Turkington\nperforming the ceremony. They\nare now at their new home on\nS. E. Fourth street, Milford.\nMr. and Mrs. H. M. Burns at\ntended the funeral of Mrs. Carrie\nHarris at the Rawlings Funeral\nHome in Greensboro, Md., on Wed\nnesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Alton King wel\ncomed their sixth child at the Mil\nford Memorial Hospital on Wed\nnesday, February 12. The little\nKing has been given the name of\nMichael Gene.\nMr. and Mrs. Robert McClellan\nof Brookhaven, Pa., spent the week\nend with Mr. and Mrs. Eugene\nParker.\nMr. and Mrs. Willey Bailey of\nFederalsburg, Md., were dinner\nguests on Sunday of their daugh\nter, Mrs. Reese Dickerson and Mr.\nDickerson.\nMr. and Mrs. Douglas Morgan\nand family and Mrs. Edith Fisher\nwere dinner guests on Sunday of\nMr. and Mrs. Loon Tucker of Wil\nmington Manor.\nLeighton Donovan is spending a\nfew days in the Milford Memorial\nHospital for observation. Richard\nWatts, who suffered a stroke on\nTuesday was removed to the Mil\nford Memorial Hospital also. Best\nwishes for a speedy recovery.\nDinner guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nHarry Glasco on Sunday Were: Mr.\nand Mrs. James Hall, Mr. and\nMrs. Robert Hill and daughter, all\nof Milford, Mr. and Mrs. James\nMessick and family of Harrington\nand Mr. and Mrs. Ralph Tucker of\nEllendale.\nMiss Judy Livingood is spending\na few days as the guest of Miss\nHelene Western while Judy's par\nents. Mr. and Mrs. Byron Livingood\nare in Bermuda.\nMr. and Mrs. Woodrow Morgan\nand daughter Joyce, Miss Janice\nDickerson,\nMorgan and infant son,\nWayne, were dinner guests on Sun\nday of Mr. and Mrs. Frank Reed\nof Milford.\nMr. and Mrs. Cecil Beideman of\nAldan, Pa., spent the week-end\nwith his mother, Mrs. Caddie Bei\ndeman and aunt, Mrs. May Wyatt.\nDonald Donovan of Milford ac\ncompanied Mr. and Mrs. Albert\nDonovan and family to Philadelphia\non Sunday where they were dinner\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. W T H. Da\nvidson. Upon returning home they\nvisited Mr. and Mrs. Harry Mark\ner of Wilmington, also Mr. Don\novan's uncle, John Wesley Abbott\nof Smyrna.\nMr. and Mrs. H. M. Burns visit\nMr. and Mrs. Wilson\nBruce\ned Mr. anti Mrs. Alvin Redden of\nMidway on Sunday afternoon.\nHarry McClellan of Chester, Pa.,\nreturned to his home on Sunday.\nafter having spent the past week\nwith Mr. and Mrs. Eugene Parker.\nMrs. Lillie Fitzgerald. Mrs. Ha\nze! Swain and Mrs. Irene Fitzger\naid left Thursday for a sight-see\ning tour to New York City,\nMrs. May Wyatt and Mrs. Caddie\nstarting with only one dollar. As\npratical matter, most every reader\nshould be able to start the fund\nwith $5,000 dollars, and then use\nthe latter amount as a Reserve for\nerrors. This Reserve would .be in\nvested more conservatively in ac\ncordance with the Babson Program\nsupplemented by, the Dewey Law of\nCycles.\nI repeat, there should be no fear\nabout being unable to select one\nstock which should double the first\nyear. Moreover, the other mathe\nmatical or investment conditions\ncan probably be met in every case,\nThe real reason why this almost un\nbelievable result has not been ob\ntained, except by a few investors,\nis because very, very few persons\nhave the patience and persistence to\ncarry out the program for 31\nThe True Secret Of Getting\nThe Million\nyears.\nBrokers, bankers, and all your\nfriends will advise quitting this\nspeculative program after the sum\nreaches $100,000, to diversify in the\n\"blue chips, and to get an income\",\nNinety-five investors out of 100 will\nfall by the wayside and do it. This\nmakes it jossible for the other 5 per\ncent who realize the value of TIME\nand stick to the 31 years to reach\nthe goal. (Go back and read again\nmy penny illustration.) This shows\nthat the real gain comes in the\nlast eight years.\nBeideman entertained to dinner on\nSunday Mr. and Mrs. Cecil Beide\nman of Aldan, Pa., Mrs. Laura\nBetts, and Mr. and Mrs. Millard\nBetts of Milford. In the afternoon\nall visited Mr. and Mrs. Oscar\nJohnson of Ellendale. Mr. Johnson\nis confined to his bed at present.\nMr. and Mrs. Harvey Swain left\nSaturday for a two weeks vacation\nat Miami. Florida.\nW omen Of The Moose\nf\nWO\ns\nQ\n\n\n\u00d6\nA\n\nAt the regular meeting of Harr\nChapter 1229, Thursday\nFeb. 27, at the Moose\nington\nevening.\nHome, Harrington, Delaware, plans\nwere made for the Mooseheart Mu\nsic Day to be held at the Moose\nHome, Harrington, Delaware. Sun\nday, March 9th at 2:00 p. m. Harr\nington Chapter 1229 has the honor\nof being Hostess Chapter with our\nSenior Regent. Irene Short, as Gen\neral Chairman. This will be an\nopen meeting and a cordial invita\ntion is extended to all Lodge and\nChapter members also to any pros\npective candidates.\nInvited Chapters are: Wilming\nton, New Castle, Seaford and Dei\nmar. All Lodges and Chapters will\nparticipate in the Mooseheart Mu\nsic March with contributions for tha\nMooseheart Music Fund. The Chap\nter will sell sandwiches and coffee\nafter the meeting. Senior Regent,\nIrene Short, asked all members to\nplease be present at this meeting.\nAfter the meeting refreshments\nwere served by Bel. and Em. Van\nderwende.\n\nLITTLE ROCK. Ark. (IP)\nOverheard in a Little Rock depart\nMother, in irritation: \"Where did\nyou lose it?\"\nLittle girl \u201ebout five years old;\n\"I don't know, it just got away.\"\nMother: \"I've warned you about\nholding on to money. I'll give you\nanother one but if you lose this,\nthat's all!\"\nAnd she handed the youngster a\nfive-dollar bill.\nHARSH IHSC'IPLIJiE\nment store:\nWest Germany's shipyards\nlaunched 323 ships with a total ton\nof about 1.100.000 tons in\n1\nnage\n1957.\nIN THE AIR FORCE\nfi\nu\n\nBy FI a In* Townsend Dickerson\n408 Lakeview Avenue\nMilford, Delaware\nMarch 5, 1958\nDear Friends:\nIn September of 1945 Hayes and\nI became engaged. It was rather\na rushed day. Hayes flew home\nfrom Panama City, Florida, for the\nweek-end (he then was in the\nArmy Corps) and the very day he\nwas expected to leave we decided\nto get my engagement ring. We\ngot our ring, told our parents and\nhustled around getting him ready\nto leave Dover Air Base by mid\nafternoon. People who become lei\nsurely engaged, dinner parties, an\nnouncement parties, etc., have al\nways been awed by me since my\nbig moment was so remote from\nthis. It was such a hurried affair\nthat I remember very little of that\nday, but the fondest memory I\nhave was Dad Dickerson putting\nhis arms around me at their home\n(then on Clarke avenue) and wel\ncoming me into his family circle.\nI never have felt that 1 had a fa\nther-in-law, but just a second fa\nther.\nLast night at six o'clock, Hayes'\nfather succumbed to cancer after\nan illness of thre? years. Dad nev\ner knew the natrre of his illness\nand only two months ago when\nHayes was home talked about the\nwork he had to do in his yard on\nSouth Washington street \"when\nspring came.\" 1 hat's why the fam\nily believes they did the right thing\nby keeping the diagnosis from him.\nIt's not quite the fair way to do,\nto the family doctors though. It\nwas hard for Dr. Laurence Fitchett\nand Dr. O. A. James to keep mak\ning excuses as to why the medi\nMILTON\nWalter W. Crouch\nPhone: Milton 4885\nJohn Duguid, comparative new\ncomer to Milton, was elected mayor\nover present Mayor Charles Barker,\nwho sought his sixth term at the\nannual town elections last Satur\nday. Mr. Duguid sought election last\nyear and lost by some 60 votes. The\ntotal vote was 365, about 100 more\nthan last year. Three members of\nthe town council were also elected\nincluding incumbents Dr. Thomas\nj. Tobin and Dr. James White,\nHammond Davidson was the third\nman to be voted into office. Holdover\nmeribers of the Milton town coun\ncil Reuben Wilkerson and Everett\nJohnson.\nFuneral services for Elmer E.\nDykes, 65, whose body was found in\na field near here Thursday morning\nwere held Sunday at 2 p. m., from\nthe William M. Short Home, in Mil\nton.\nSeveral members, of the Goshen\nMethodist Woman s Society of\nChristian Service, attended the an\nnual spring meeting of the Dover\nDistrict WSCS. This year's session\nwas held in the Avenue Methodist\nChurch, Milford.\nMr. Dykes died of natural causes.\nHe suffered a heart attack after\nmaking a trip to town for groceries.\nSon of the late Samuel E. and Anna\nDykes of Greenwood, he had lived\nin Milton several years. He is sur\nvived by his wife and a sister,\nMrs. Bertha Trice, both of the\nGreenwood area.\nA \"Kick-off\" dinner meeting was\nheld in Goshen Methodist Fellow\nship Hall, on Thursday evening,\nThe Red Cross Planning Committee\nmeeting began with a dinner which\nwas supervised by Mrs. Leon King,\npresident of the WSCS. Samuel\nShapiro, chairman of this Area's\nRed Cross Fund Drive, conducted\nthe business and planning sessions.\nAt 8:00 p. m., last Thursday even\ning, many interested citizens of the\ncommunity the Chamber of Com\nmerce showing of the Sesqui-Cen\ntennial movies, in Assembly Room\nof Goshen Church. Mr. Thomas\nHughes, president of that organi\nzation presided and Mr. and Mrs.\nCharles Barker were host and\nhostess for the social hour which\nfollowed in the Fellowship Hall.\nHarold Libis is expected to\nreturn to his home on Union Street\nafter having been a patient in Beebe\nHospital. Lewes for many days.\nEdward Argo was admitted to the\nMilford Memorial Hospital last Sun\nday afternoon following a sudden\nheart attack at his home in North\nMilton. He is reported progressing\nrapidly and his family report that\nhe will be home early next week.\nMr. and Mrs. Robert D. Lingo\nand cnildren, of Milford, were Sun-[\nday dinner guests with his parents,\nMr. and Mrs. R. Davis Lingo, in\nMilton.\nOn Sunday, Mrs. Eliza Dutton en\ntertained her brother, Harvey Wil\nof Lepsic and Mr. and Mrs.\nRalston Pepper of Gravel Hill.\nMr. and Mrs. Whitley Williams\nspent the week-enr in Dover with\nhis sister, Mrs. Leiha Saxton. Be\nfore returning to their home in Mil\nton the Williams spent Sunday\nevening with Mr. and Mrs. Max\nHarrington, in Milford.\nMr. and Mrs. John Coverdale, of\nLincoln spent Tuesday with Mr. and\nMrs, Reed Leverage. On Friday af\nter noon, Mrs. Virgie White and\ndaughter, Joan, of Overbrook, visit\ned with the Leverages and on\nSunday. Mr. and Mrs. Leverage en\ntertained Mr. and Mrs. Henry Dra\nper. of Milford. Mrs. Delema Outten,\nof Georgetown and Miss Mary Reed,\nMilton.\nMrs. Charles Hudson and son.\nChuck, of Lewes spent Monday with\nher aunt. Mrs. Clarence Reed and\nfamily on Broad St.\nMr. and Mrs. Clarence Melvin, of\nMilford were Sunday afternoon\nguests with Mrs. Mary Quig and\nsen\nJohn T. Crouch at the Lester E.\nClendaniel residence, on Broad St.\nMrs. T. Raymond Spencer is now\na patient in the Peninsula General\nHospital. Salisbury. Maryland. Mrs.\nSpencer underwent surgery early\nthis week. Mr. Spencer was the\nguest of his son Dyson Spencer and\nfamily during the first few days\nof this week.\nMrs. Alfred Gross is attending a\nManager's Convention for Field En\nterprise. World Book Encyclopedia\nDivision, held in Atlantic City.\ncine wasn't working miracles, why\nhe could not return home and leave\nthe hospital. It really was diffi\ncult many times for them, but\nDad's not knowing gave him much\nhope.\nThe memory of Dad's visit to\nKansas one year ago has made\nmany happy hours for him the last\nfew months of his illness. He flew\nin a commercial airliner to Kansas\nCity, his very first such flight.\nMother and Dad D. were with us six\nweeks and during their stay we\ntried to show them as much of the\nmid-west as possible\u2014the Eisen\nhower homestead in Abilene, Tru\nman's home in Independence, the\nArmy Command and Staff School\nat Fort Leavenworth, and Hayes\nreceived special permission to take\nhis parents in the flight line to let\nthem see the jet bomber that Hayes\nflies in SAC.\nIt's impossible to enumerate the\nnames of people who have been so\nconcerned over Dud's welfare. So\nmany visited him, so many sent\ncards, so many brought food that\nthey hoped might please his wan\ning appetite. It's hard to visit a\nfriend or relative as i'j as Dad\nDickerson was, but his stream of\nvisitors continued until the very\nend. Last Saturday was an excep\ntional day. Dad was very keen at\nthat time and many of his friends\nwere greatly entertained by his\nsense of humor, even at that late\nhour in his life.\nNo one would have wanted Dad\nto have suffered one hour longer,\nbut I shall terribly miss my second\nfather.\nAlways,\nElaine Townsend Dickerson\nHOUSTON\nMrs. Viola Thlstlewood\nPhone: Milford 4944\nThought for the week: \"God knew\nwhat He was doing when he gave\nsome folks great minds\u2014and then\ncreated the rest of us to ask them\nquestions\".\nChurch news for Sunday, March\n9th!\nSunday School at 10 a. m., with\nRobert H. Yerkes, Sr., General\nSupt. Alvin Brown, Junior Supt.;\nMrs. Charles Pearson, Cradle Roll\nSupt. Last Sunday, there were 147\npresent\nThe service of worship begins\nwith the prelude with Mrs. Agnes\nWebb at the piano. Call to worship\nby the pastor. Rev. Ray Kirwan.\nThe Senior and Junior choirs will\nhave special numbers. The minister\nwill deliver the sermon. There were\n89 present last Sunday.\nThe MYF will hold its meeting\nat 6:45 p. m.\nThe O. U. R. Sunday School class\nwill hold a chicken and dumpling\nsupper in the Fire Hall, Friday,\nMarch 7. Prices adult $1.25; chil\ndren, 75c. Admission by ticket only.\nThe Fellowship pancake and\nsausage breakfast sponsored by the\nMethodist Men, will be held in the\nLibby, McNeill, and Libby cafeteria,\nSunday, March 16th. A cordial in\nyitation is extended to all.\nThere were 25 men from Hous\n^n w h G attended the Men's Len\nen Communion Breakfast in Cal\nvary Methodist Church, Milford, last\ngunday morning.\nThe WSCS will hold its regular\nmonthly meeting on Thursday even\ning, March 13, at the fire hall. Hos\ntesses will be Mrs. Lida Marvel,\nMrs. Hilda Mulholland and Mrs.\nSarah Webb.\nThe Chancel Choir will hold a\nbake at Yost's store on Saturday\nmorning, April 5 ,at 10 a. m. More\nabout this later, but we just want\ne d to keep the date open.\nWe are glad to report Mrs. Ruth\nBuarque, who suffered a severe at\ntack of quinsey last week, is im\nproved at this time.\nMrs. Evelyn Greenlee entered\nMilford Memorial Hospital, on Tues\nday morning suffering from a kid\nney stone since Sunday.\nMrs. Phyllis Minner is a patient\nin Milford Memorial Hospital,\nwhere she underwent surgery on\nMonday morning.\nWe are sorry to report the ill\nness of Mrs. Willis Clifton and\nhope she makes a speedy recovery.\nThe condition of Herbert Carter\nremains about the same. No change\neither way.\nMr. and Mrs. Willis Voshell en\ntertained the following guests on\nSunday. Mr. and Mrs. Raymond\nKarpin and son, Randy and Mrs.\nMyrtle Hill, of Chester, Pa., and\njyi r and Mrs. Paul McNatt and\nson t 0 f Milford,\nMr. and Mrs. Emory Webb visit\ned Mr. and Mrs. Franklin Slaughter\nof Ridgely, on Sunday afternoon.\nBoth Mr. and Mrs. Slaughter have\nbeen ill.\nMrs. Maggie Hudson of Milford,\nspent several days last week with\nMrs. Minnie Armour. Mrs. Sallie\nClendaniel of Dover, was a caller\none day last week also.\nMr. and Mrs. Thomas Parvis and\ndaughter were week-end guests of\nhis brother, Josiah M. Parvis and\nfamily.\nMr. and Mrs. Jffhn P. lycmmon,\nJr., and daughter Gayle, spent the\nweek-end in New Jersey as the\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Vance\nBaechelor and family.\nMr. and Mrs. Franklin Morgan,\ndaughter. Connie and Mrs. Anna\nTuttle were dinner guests of the\nMarshall Harts in Magnolia, on\nSunday.\nMiss Joyce Ann Buarque spent\nthe week-end with friends in Wil\nmington.\nThe annual Houston PTA Auction\nwill he held in the Fire Hall on\nFriday evening. March 14, beginning\nat 8 o'clock. Plenty of nice articles\nfor sale as well as good cakes, pies\ncandy, etc. Everyone come out and\nhelp this worthwhile organization.\nTROUGHS TO DISAPPEAR\nUP) Frank\nMONTREAL\nDowd, city waterworks superinten\ndent, says Montreal's remaining\nwater troughs for horses will be re\nmoved as they fall into dissepair.\n\"They serve no useful purpose now\nand are a nuisance to pedestrians,\nmotorists and snow removal crews.\"\nhe said","height":"25224","width":"20256"}}
